sentence: SVMK (SVMK), the parent of online-survey firm SurveyMonkey, debuted strongly on Wall Street, with shares soaring 42% to $17.00 on Wednesday.
The Silicon Valley-based company, the seventh in the region to go public this year, had traded for as much as $20.00.
The initial public offering raised $180 million on the sale of 15 million shares at $12 each.
The company's IPO price of $12 gave it a market cap of $1.46 billion - short of the $2 billion private investors thought it was worth in 2014.
A potential concern among investors is the $27.2 million SVMK lost in the first six months of this year despite 14% growth in revenue to $121.2 million.
It lost $19.1 million in the year-ago period.
"This is just the first step in a long journey," SVMK Chief Financial Officer Tim Maly tells Barron's in a phone interview.
He pointed to its "long history of robust cash flow," which hit $45 million last year, and 600,000 paying subscribers.
The 19-year-old company had more than 16 million active users in the past year.

SVMK's shareholders include Salesforce.com's (CRM) ventures unit, which announced this month a $40 million private placement at the IPO price; Tiger Global Management ; and a revocable trust for Facebook (FB) Chief Operating Officer Sheryl Sandberg, widow of the company's former Chief ExecutiveDave Goldberg.
Sandberg, who is on SurveyMonkey's board, has said she plans to donate all of her shares to charity.
In the past three years, SurveyMonkey has struck up partnerships with Microsoft (MSFT), Alphabet's (GOOGL) Google, and Salesforce, according to SVMK's IPO filing.
"The Salesforce investment is great validation, given its leadership in cloud computing," Maly says.
